David Schwimmer, a palaeontologist at Columbus State University in Georgia, told LiveScience: ‘It's a case where a newborn shark ate a newborn turtle and died.'

The fossilised poo, which is also known as a coprolite, measures almost four centimetres long and was discovered in a fossil bed close to the South Carolina coastline.

Between 70 million and 80 million years ago, the area was where the baby shark was born - in a tidal estuary where the sea met inland rivers.

